+--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
+11. Architecture and technical decisions
+This section documents the key architectural decisions and why they were made. It is not intended as implementation documentation but as a record of the reasoning behind the structure.
+
+Chat-first interface
+We chose a chat interface rather than a dashboard or a notes interface because it is the most natural way people already interact with AI systems. It eliminates onboarding friction and allows a single input to serve multiple purposes: capturing content, asking questions, setting reminders, requesting audits, and setting preferences. The user never needs to decide which mode they are in.
+
+Atomic memories, not documents
+The most important architectural decision. Every other tool stores documents or highlight collections. We store atomic ideas. A 3000 word article becomes 7 or 8 self-contained memory objects. This has several consequences: search retrieval is far more precise, context window usage in RAG is dramatically lower (retrieving 7 atoms instead of a full article), recall can target specific ideas rather than whole sources, and contradiction detection can work at the level of individual claims rather than documents.
+
+PostgreSQL with pgvector
+We keep vector search inside the primary database rather than using a separate vector store. This simplifies the architecture, reduces operational complexity, and keeps semantic search co-located with relational queries. For our scale this is the correct tradeoff.
+
+Qwen Cloud for all AI tasks
+We use three Qwen models for different tasks. qwen-plus for extraction and belief audits where quality matters most. qwen-turbo for relationship detection where speed matters and the task is classification rather than generation. qwen3.7-plus for deep RAG chat responses where reasoning depth is required. text-embedding-v4 for all embedding generation. Using different models for different tasks rather than one model for everything is a deliberate cost and quality optimization.
+
+Temperature zero for extraction
+All structured extraction calls run at temperature zero. This makes outputs deterministic and consistent. The same content run through extraction twice produces nearly identical memory atoms. This consistency is essential for a system that is building a knowledge graph over time.
+
+RAG with atomic retrieval
+When a user asks a question through the chat interface, the system embeds the query, retrieves the most semantically relevant memory atoms, injects them into the system prompt, and generates a response grounded in what the user has actually saved. This is retrieval augmented generation with atomic units rather than document chunks. The result is more precise, uses far less context, and stays grounded in the user's own knowledge rather than the model's general training.
+
+MCP as external interface
+The MCP server is a thin adapter layer over existing backend services. It does not contain business logic. It validates inputs and calls the same services the chat interface uses. This means any improvement to the underlying services automatically improves the MCP interface. External agents get the same quality of memory tools that internal users get.
+
+Deployment
+Backend runs on Alibaba Cloud ECS with Nginx as reverse proxy and systemd for process management. Frontend is deployed on Vercel. Database is Neon PostgreSQL. This separation keeps infrastructure costs low while maintaining reliability.
+--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
+12. What we do not do
+Clarity about what Crowscap is not is as important as clarity about what it is.
+
+  oo   We do not claim to know the truth. Crowscap evaluates how well-supported beliefs are based on what the user has saved. It does not have access to ground truth. It works with the evidence the user provides.
+  oo   We do not tell users they are wrong. The system surfaces tensions and gaps. It asks questions. The user decides what to update and what to keep.
+  oo   We do not automate thinking. The goal is to help people think better, not to think for them. Crowscap is a tool for intellectual development, not a replacement for it.
+  oo   We do not manage tasks or projects. Crowscap handles knowledge and memory. Life reminders are a lightweight exception: they fire once and disappear. They do not enter the memory lifecycle.
+  oo   We do not save everything. Content that does not pass basic quality signals should not enter the memory graph. Accidental saves, irrelevant links, and low-quality content should be preventable and reversible.
+  oo   We do not surface content the user has archived. Archived means archived. It is retrievable if the user goes looking, but it does not appear in search, recall, or audits.
+--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
+13. Product roadmap
+What follows is an honest account of where the product is and where it is going. Timelines are intentionally absent because they depend on team size, user feedback, and what we learn.
+
+Current: Foundation (July 2026)
+The core loop is working. Multi-format capture, atomic extraction, semantic search, relationship detection, belief audit, spaced recall, preference learning, conversation persistence, archiving, and MCP server are all live. The product is deployed and usable at crowscap.xyz.
+
+Next: Retention and trust
+The immediate priorities are proving that the habit forms and that users trust the system with their real knowledge.
+  oo   Onboard 50 real users and measure day-7 retention as the primary signal.
+  oo   Platform Better Redesign, expecially the landing page.
+  oo   Fix known edge cases in capture: YouTube Shorts, accidental links, WhatsApp group invites.
+  oo   Add the confirmation step for URL captures before processing.
+  oo   Add 30-second undo after any capture.
+  oo   Improve the recall selection logic to prioritize contextual relevance over overdue date.
+  oo   Add the "why this now" explanation to every recall card.
+  oo   Tighten intent classification so conversational messages do not trigger unnecessary memory search.
+  oo   Build the evaluation harness comparing atomic RAG against naive document RAG with real metrics.
+
+Following: Depth and proactivity
+Once retention is proven, the product deepens.
+  oo   Proactive ignorance gap surfacing: the background intelligence layer that finds credible counterpoints to saved beliefs and surfaces them gently during recall.
+  oo   Action tracking: converting action-type memories into trackable commitments with status.
+  oo   Memory compression: identifying clusters of near-duplicate memories and offering to merge them into one stronger canonical memory.
+  oo   Richer memory detail view showing source, all related memories, recall history, and evidence strength.
+  oo   Public evidence integration directly into the belief audit, not just as leads but as retrievable sources.
+
+Later: Platform and mobile
+As the core product proves its value, distribution expands.
+  oo   Mobile-first recall and notification flows so recall reaches users where they actually are.
+  oo   Browser extension for one-click capture without opening the app.
+  oo   Deeper MCP integration and developer documentation for teams building on the memory layer.
+  oo   API tier for developers who want to embed Crowscap memory into their own products.
+  oo   Team and shared knowledge features for organizations.
+--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
+14. Long-term vision
+The long-term vision for Crowscap is to become the most trusted personal memory intelligence system in the world.
+
+Trust in this context means: when Crowscap tells you something about what you believe, you can rely on it. When it surfaces a tension between two ideas you hold, you know the tension is real. When it tells you your confidence in something is low, you trust that assessment. When it surfaces a counterpoint to a belief, you know it is credible.
+That kind of trust is built slowly and lost instantly. Every product decision we make should be evaluated against whether it builds or erodes trust.
+
+Ambient capture (long-term)
+The most ambitious version of capture requires no deliberate action from the user. A browser extension runs quietly in the background, noticing what the user reads, how long they spend on it, what they re-read or highlight. At the end of a reading session, it asks: "You spent 12 minutes on this article. Want me to extract what matters?" One tap yes. The capture happens from behavior, not from a deliberate decision to save. This almost completely eliminates the capture friction that is currently the biggest barrier to the habit forming.
+
+Memory as infrastructure
+Through the MCP server, Crowscap becomes a memory layer that any AI agent can use. In the future, a user could be working inside any AI-powered tool, a writing assistant, a research tool, a business planning agent, and that agent could call Crowscap to access what this specific person has learned and believes. The user's knowledge follows them everywhere, not just inside Crowscap's own interface. This shifts Crowscap from a product people use to infrastructure that powers intelligent experiences wherever the user works.
+
+The wiser user
+The ultimate measure of whether Crowscap is working is not daily active users or retention rates. It is whether people who use Crowscap consistently become meaningfully better at using what they know. They defend their beliefs with more precision. They notice when they are holding a belief with insufficient evidence. They apply what they have learned to real decisions at the right moment. They know the difference between what they understand and what they merely recognize.
+That is a harder outcome to measure. It is also the only outcome that matters.
+--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
+15. Success metrics
+Metrics should measure what actually matters, not what is easy to count.
+
+Primary metrics
+  oo   Day-7 retention: the percentage of users who return within 7 days of first capture without being explicitly reminded. This is the signal that the habit is forming.
+  oo   Recall engagement rate: the percentage of surfaced recall items that receive a substantive response rather than being dismissed or skipped.
+  oo   Capture-to-recall ratio: for users who have been active more than 30 days, are they recalling things they saved earlier? This indicates the system is functioning as a memory system, not just a capture tool.
+
+Secondary metrics
+  oo   Belief audit usage: how many users have run at least one belief audit? This indicates they are using the epistemic features and not just the capture and search features.
+  oo   Contradiction discovery: how many users have seen and engaged with a contradiction or tension surfaced by the system? Engagement with this feature is a signal of the product's unique value being experienced.
+  oo   Preference profile completeness: users with more complete preference profiles get more tailored experiences. Tracking how quickly profiles fill in indicates how well the preference detection is working.
+
+What we do not optimize for
+  oo   Time in app: Crowscap should be efficient. A user who gets what they need in 5 minutes and leaves is doing exactly what the product is designed for.
+  oo   Number of memories saved: more is not better. Quality and recall engagement matter more than volume.
+  oo   Daily active users before retention is proven: growing a user base before the product is reliably valuable is building on a weak foundation.
+--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
+16. Open questions
+These are questions the team needs to work through. They are not blockers but they require honest answers before the relevant parts of the product are built.
+
+  oo   What is the right monetization model? Freemium SaaS seems obvious, but what specifically is free and what is paid? The epistemic features (belief audit, contradiction detection) are the most valuable and should probably be gated on paid tiers. But if they are gated, users may never discover why Crowscap is different from other tools.
+  oo   How do we handle content that the user has saved that is later shown to be factually wrong? The system should not silently update beliefs without the user's involvement. But surfacing the information in a way that does not feel like an accusation requires careful design.
+  oo   What is the right cadence for proactive recall? Too frequent and it becomes an obligation. Too infrequent and the habit does not form. This will need empirical testing with real users across different usage patterns.
+  oo   How do we handle users who save very low quality content consistently? Do we flag it? Ignore it? Filter it silently? The answer has implications for user trust and product integrity.
+  oo   When do we build mobile? The product is currently web only. Recall and notifications are significantly more powerful on mobile. But mobile adds engineering complexity at a stage where focus matters more than coverage.
+       Crowscap PRD v1.0   |   July 2026   |   Internal and confidential
+                                       
